## Why HTTP-Only Correlation Fails

Inside HTTP, middleware and log scopes give you a natural request boundary. In async processing, there is no ambient request context. A worker can start minutes later on another machine.

So the rule changes:

1. Put correlation data in the message envelope.
2. Rehydrate it into worker log scope when processing starts.
3. Pass it forward on all follow-up messages.

## A Minimal Envelope Contract

Keep message contracts explicit. Do not rely on hidden ambient state.

```csharp
public sealed record MessageEnvelope<T>(
    string MessageType,
    string CorrelationId,
    string? TraceParent,
    DateTimeOffset OccurredAtUtc,
    T Payload);

public sealed record ScheduleWorkOrderRequest(
    Guid WorkOrderId,
    Guid TechnicianId,
    DateOnly PlannedDate);
```

`CorrelationId` remains your app-facing key. `TraceParent` is optional but useful when bridging to tracing systems that can continue a parent context.

## Producer Side: Publish With Identity

From your API command handler, read ids from your request accessor and include them in the outgoing envelope.

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;

public sealed class WorkOrderPublisher
{
    private readonly IRequestIdentityAccessor _identity;
    private readonly IMessageBus _bus;

    public WorkOrderPublisher(IRequestIdentityAccessor identity, IMessageBus bus)
    {
        _identity = identity;
        _bus = bus;
    }

    public Task PublishScheduleRequestAsync(
        ScheduleWorkOrderRequest payload,
        CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var envelope = new MessageEnvelope<ScheduleWorkOrderRequest>(
            MessageType: "workorders.schedule.requested",
            CorrelationId: _identity.GetCorrelationId(),
            TraceParent: Activity.Current?.Id,
            OccurredAtUtc: DateTimeOffset.UtcNow,
            Payload: payload);

        return _bus.PublishAsync(envelope, ct);
    }
}
```

The key design choice is intentional duplication: identity fields live in metadata, not buried inside payload models.

## Consumer Side: Rehydrate Scope Early

When a worker receives a message, create a processing scope before any domain logic.

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

public sealed class ScheduleWorkOrderConsumer
{
    private readonly ILogger<ScheduleWorkOrderConsumer> _logger;

    public ScheduleWorkOrderConsumer(ILogger<ScheduleWorkOrderConsumer> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    public async Task HandleAsync(
        MessageEnvelope<ScheduleWorkOrderRequest> envelope,
        CancellationToken ct)
    {
        using var activity = new Activity("Consume workorders.schedule.requested");
        if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(envelope.TraceParent))
        {
            activity.SetParentId(envelope.TraceParent);
        }

        activity.Start();

        using (_logger.BeginScope(new Dictionary<string, object>
        {
            ["CorrelationId"] = envelope.CorrelationId,
            ["TraceId"] = activity.TraceId.ToString(),
            ["MessageType"] = envelope.MessageType,
            ["WorkOrderId"] = envelope.Payload.WorkOrderId
        }))
        {
            _logger.LogInformation("Scheduling started");

            await Task.Delay(5, ct);

            _logger.LogInformation("Scheduling completed");
        }
    }
}
```

If processing throws, failure logs still carry the same `CorrelationId` used by the initiating HTTP request.

## Queue Header Mapping (Transport-Agnostic)

Different brokers expose metadata differently, but the mapping is the same:

- `correlation_id` -> `CorrelationId`
- `traceparent` -> `TraceParent`
- `message_type` -> `MessageType`

Example sender abstraction:

```csharp
public interface IMessageBus
{
    Task PublishAsync<T>(MessageEnvelope<T> envelope, CancellationToken ct);
}

public sealed class JsonMessageBus : IMessageBus
{
    private readonly IQueueClient _queue;

    public JsonMessageBus(IQueueClient queue)
    {
        _queue = queue;
    }

    public Task PublishAsync<T>(MessageEnvelope<T> envelope, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var body = System.Text.Json.JsonSerializer.Serialize(envelope.Payload);

        var headers = new Dictionary<string, string>
        {
            ["correlation_id"] = envelope.CorrelationId,
            ["traceparent"] = envelope.TraceParent ?? string.Empty,
            ["message_type"] = envelope.MessageType,
            ["occurred_at"] = envelope.OccurredAtUtc.ToString("O")
        };

        return _queue.SendAsync(body, headers, ct);
    }
}
```

This lets you migrate from one broker to another without rewriting correlation strategy.

## Scheduled and Recurring Jobs

Recurring jobs often do not have a user request behind them. In that case, generate a new correlation id at execution start and keep it stable for that run.

```csharp
public sealed class OverdueWorkOrderSweepJob
{
    private readonly ILogger<OverdueWorkOrderSweepJob> _logger;

    public OverdueWorkOrderSweepJob(ILogger<OverdueWorkOrderSweepJob> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    public async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var correlationId = $"job-overdue-sweep-{DateTime.UtcNow:yyyyMMddHHmmss}";

        using (_logger.BeginScope(new Dictionary<string, object>
        {
            ["CorrelationId"] = correlationId,
            ["JobName"] = "OverdueWorkOrderSweep"
        }))
        {
            _logger.LogInformation("Sweep started");

            await Task.Delay(5, ct);

            _logger.LogInformation("Sweep finished");
        }
    }
}
```

That gives operations one id to trace each scheduled run even without an incoming HTTP call.

## Idempotency and Retries

Retries can flood logs with near-duplicate entries. Add attempt metadata to keep runs understandable.

```json
{
  "message": "Work order scheduling failed",
  "CorrelationId": "wo_8fd2a0f0c2ad4cb8b85c",
  "MessageType": "workorders.schedule.requested",
  "Attempt": 3,
  "MaxAttempts": 5,
  "WorkOrderId": "2a53d241-233f-48f8-a720-b9dd9f41f3a7"
}
```

Keep `CorrelationId` constant across retries. Change attempt counters, not identity.

## Security Notes for Async Boundaries

- Validate incoming correlation headers before enqueue.
- Cap correlation id length and allowed characters.
- Avoid putting PII into ids and queue headers.
- If crossing trust boundaries, consider generating a new internal correlation id and storing external id separately.

## Summary

Async-safe correlation needs explicit design:

1. put identity in every message envelope,
2. rehydrate it into worker scopes immediately,
3. preserve it across publish-consume hops,
4. generate deterministic ids for scheduler-originated flows.

With this in place, you can follow one incident from browser click to queue consumer to downstream API calls without losing context.